<div id="ftn84">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><a href="#_ftnref84" id="_ftn84" name="_ftn84" title=""><span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span class="MsoFootnoteReference">[84]</span></span></a> A 2019 Asia Society report, in discussing the Belt and Road Initiative, concluded: “Chinese officials invoke the principles of ‘noninterference’ and ‘respect for local law’ to distance themselves from aspects of BRI projects that fall short of international standards and best practices. But developing countries often lack the necessary institutions to support adherence to the rule of law or the application of international standards….The lack of rigorous oversight in poorer developing countries with limited capabilities or weak governance has resulted in a range of problems that have begun to alienate local communities and taint the BRI brand.” Daniel R. Russel and Blake Berger, Asia Society Policy Institute, “Navigating the Belt and Road Initiative,” June 2019, p. 11. https://asiasociety.org/sites/default/files/2019-06/Navigating%20the%20Belt%20and%20Road%20Initiative_2.pdf (accessed January 5, 2020).</p>
